Dear FrancisTafe, thx for the feedback but... excuse me... what "problem of conversion for non user of python" do you mean?

This is the solution of the clash in Java. You can copy it into the IDE and it works 100% correct.

You have solved 35 puzzles in Java and even have the certificate. What do you dislike on this solution.

Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
int W = in.nextInt();
int H = in.nextInt();
int[][] input = new int[H][W];
for (int i = 0; i < H; i++) {
    for (int j = 0; j < W; j++) {
        input[i][j] = in.nextInt();
    }
}

int[][] integral = new int[H+1][W+1];
integral[1][1] = input[0][0];
for (int row = 0; row < H; row++ ) {
    for (int col = 0; col < W; col++ ) {
        integral[row+1][col+1] = input[row][col]
                + integral[row+1][col]
                + integral[row][col+1]
                - integral[row][col];
    }
}

for (int row = 1; row < H+1; row++ ) {
    for (int col = 1; col < W+1; col++ ) {
        System.out.print(integral[row][col]);
        if (col!=W) {
            System.out.print(' ');
        }
    }
    System.out.println();
}

By the way, the integral image is a generally used array.

